  "prompt": "How often should employees get a performance review?",
  "response": "Performance reviews are typically conducted on an annual basis in many organizations, but increasingly, companies are finding value in more frequent evaluations. Here\u2019s a general guideline:\n\n1. **Annual Reviews:** These are comprehensive evaluations covering an entire year's performance. They usually influence decisions on promotions, raises, and bonuses, and set goals for the upcoming year.\n\n2. **Semi-Annual Reviews:** Conducting reviews twice a year can help ensure that goals set during the annual review are on track, while still allowing for mid-year adjustments.\n\n3. **Quarterly Reviews:** These offer regular checkpoints, making it easier to make adjustments in real-time. They help keep employees aligned with company goals and reduce the pressure on a single annual review.\n\n4. **Continuous Feedback:** A more modern approach involves continuous feedback throughout the year, which can be informal one-on-one meetings or check-ins. This enables ongoing development and quicker course corrections.\n\nThe best approach depends on the organization\u2019s culture, industry norms, and specific goals. The trend is shifting towards more frequent, informal check-ins that focus on growth and development rather than just evaluation.",
